      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are signs of vitamin D and zinc deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin D deficiency symptoms: fatigue, bone pain, muscle weakness, frequent infections, depression, slow wound healing, and hair loss. Severe deficiency causes rickets in children and osteomalacia in adults. Zinc deficiency symptoms: impaired taste and smell, frequent infections, slow wound healing, hair loss, diarrhea, and in men, reduced testosterone. Because symptoms overlap (fatigue, infections, hair loss), dual deficiency can be difficult to distinguish from single-nutrient deficiency without blood testing. A simple blood test for 25-hydroxyvitamin D and serum zinc levels can confirm both deficiencies.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take vitamin D3 or D2?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is the preferred form. D3 is the same form your skin produces when exposed to sunlight, and studies show it raises and maintains blood 25(OH)D levels more effectively than D2 (ergocalciferol). A meta-analysis in the American Journal of Clinical Nutrition found that D3 was 87% more potent than D2 in raising vitamin D levels and produced 2-3x greater storage of the vitamin. D2 is plant-derived (suitable for strict vegans), while D3 is traditionally sourced from lanolin (sheep wool) but is now available from lichen for vegan formulations. Always choose D3 unless you specifically need a vegan D2 product.' },
