    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin D and Zinc Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Why take vitamin D and zinc together?</summary><p>They support complementary immune mechanisms: D3 activates T-cells (adaptive immunity), zinc supports neutrophils and NK cells (innate immunity). Dual deficiency increases respiratory infection risk more than single deficiency. Zinc may enhance vitamin D receptor function.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much vitamin D and zinc should I take daily?</summary><p>D3: 600-2,000 IU (upper limit 4,000 IU). Zinc: 8-11mg (upper limit 40mg). A combo gummy with 1,000-2,000 IU D3 and 10-15mg zinc covers most adults. Higher doses require medical supervision.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take vitamin D and zinc at the same time?</summary><p>Yes. No negative interactions exist. Zinc may enhance D receptor function. Take both with a fat-containing meal for optimal absorption. Breakfast with eggs or avocado is ideal.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What are signs of vitamin D and zinc deficiency?</summary><p>Both: fatigue, frequent infections, hair loss. D-specific: bone pain, depression, muscle weakness. Zinc-specific: impaired taste/smell, slow wound healing. Blood testing for 25(OH)D and serum zinc confirms deficiency.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take vitamin D3 or D2?</summary><p>D3 (cholecalciferol) is 87% more potent than D2 in raising blood levels. D3 is the form your skin produces from sunlight. Always choose D3 unless you need vegan D2 specifically.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When is the best time to take vitamin D and zinc gummies?</summary><p>With your fattiest meal — D is fat-soluble. Taking D with fat-containing food increased blood levels by 50% vs empty stomach. Zinc also absorbs better with food. Avoid taking zinc with high-fiber or calcium-heavy meals.</p></details>

